This brings the total number of cases confirmed in the
country to 322,640 out of the 3,322,325 tests conducted so far. "Of the cases, 17 are Kenyans while 9 are foreigners.
15 are males and 11 are females. The youngest is a one-year-old child while the
oldest is 75 years,” said the Ministry in a statement on Friday. In terms of county distribution, Nairobi leads with 14 cases
followed by Nakuru 3, Kiambu 2, Kwale 2, Siaya 2, Mombasa 1, Nyamira 1 and
Turkana 1. MoH also noted that 29 patients recovered out of which 27
are from the Home-Based Isolation and Care program while 2 are from various
health facilities countrywide. Total recoveries now stand at 302,966 of which 250,158 are
from the Home-Based Care and Isolation program, while 52,808 were discharged
from various health facilities countrywide. No deaths were reported and therefore the cumulative
fatalities still stand at 5,633. The ministry further said that 137 patients are currently
admitted in various health facilities countrywide, while 593 are under the
Home-Based Isolation and Care program. “3 patients are in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU) and all of
them are on ventilatory support,” said Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe in
a statement. “Another 24 patients are on supplemental oxygen and all of
them are in the general wards. No patient is in the High Dependency Unit
(HDU).” On the vaccination exercise, CS Kagwe announced that 16,019,611
vaccines had been administered across the country as of February 17, 2022. Of these, 7,619,607 are partially vaccinated while those
fully vaccinated are 7,297,113. “The total number of vaccines administered in the last 24
hours is 69,574 while the total number of people fully vaccinated in the last
24 hours is 40,199,” stated the CS. He added that 863,700 are doses administered to those
between 15 to 17 years while 239,191 are booster doses.  “The uptake of the second dose among those who received
their first dose was at 63.2%. The proportion of adults fully vaccinated was
26.8%. The Government is working towards vaccinating a targeted population of
27,246,033,” said Kagwe.